Morning Bear has awakened from hibernation to release their first new music in 6 years. After a series of devastating events and losses, including the global pandemic, the death of three close friends in separate tragedies, a severe injury, and battles with anxiety and depression, band leader John Runnels was uncertain about a return to music. However, after taking time to heal and process, Morning Bear returns with songs inspired by those experiences; exploring themes of grueling work and sacrifice in the face of uncertainty, of giving ourselves grace, of finding things to hold onto in the darkest of times, and of the resilience of the human spirit.  The brainchild of Denver-based singer/songwriter John Runnels, Morning Bear is an orchestral indie folk project that channels emotion through vivid imagery and intricate melodies. Characterized by highly dynamic compositions, Morning Bear’s music is a synthesis of the calm and delicate stylings of artists like Bon Iver and Jose Gonzalez with the complexity and depth of the Fleet Foxes and Sufjan Stevens. Featuring soaring vocals and atypical arrangements including cello, violin, piano and more, Morning Bear provides a textured landscape behind pop-influenced hooks.  Since forming in early 2014, Morning Bear has released two EP's, has toured extensively both nationally and internationally, and has had their music on rotation at college and public radio, including NPR. In 2018, Morning Bear was invited to play Red Rocks amphitheater for the Film on the Rocks series. Morning Bear's most recent single "You're Right" has racked up over 240,000 listens on Spotify. -Past live radio sessions at KVOQ Open Air (An NPR affiliate station in Denver), WEMF in Boston, MA, KRFC in Fort Collins, CO, KPSU in Portland, OR, and KUCI in Irvine, CA.

‘At Last’ has been the most important song of my career. Over the past 10 years, I have sung this song for thousands and thousands of people all around the world, on fancy stages, at friends’ weddings, and in hospital recovery rooms. To me, this song is about the glory of finally, finally getting what you’ve always dreamed of. Yes, ‘At Last’ is about happiness, but also about relief. When I sing this song, I know triumph tastes sweeter when you wait for it.
